<doc xmlns="vsml">
  <heading>
    <weight>1</weight>
    <run>
      <colour>#000000</colour>VSML!</run>
  </heading>
  <heading>
    <weight>2</weight>
    <run>
      <colour>#000000</colour>Headings</run>
  </heading>
  <paragraph>
    <run>
      <colour>#000000</colour>#1 Makes headings like this!</run>
  </paragraph>
  <paragraph>
    <run>
      <colour>#000000</colour>Headings are made by using a # followed by a number 1 - 6. </run>
  </paragraph>
  <heading>
    <weight>1</weight>
    <run>
      <colour>#000000</colour>They start this big. (1)</run>
  </heading>
  <heading>
    <weight>2</weight>
    <run>
      <colour>#000000</colour> And they get smaller (2)</run>
  </heading>
  <heading>
    <weight>3</weight>
    <run>
      <colour>#000000</colour> and smaller (3)</run>
  </heading>
  <heading>
    <weight>4</weight>
    <run>
      <colour>#000000</colour> and smaller (4)</run>
  </heading>
  <heading>
    <weight>5</weight>
    <run>
      <colour>#000000</colour> and smaller (5)</run>
  </heading>
  <heading>
    <weight>6</weight>
    <run>
      <colour>#000000</colour> and smaller (6)</run>
  </heading>
  <heading>
    <weight>2</weight>
    <run>
      <colour>#000000</colour>Paragraphs</run>
  </heading>
  <paragraph>
    <run>
      <colour>#000000</colour>To add a paragraph, just type away! </run>
  </paragraph>
  <paragraph>
    <run>
      <colour>#000000</colour>Paragraphs can be written in natural english like this is.</run>
  </paragraph>
  <heading>
    <weight>2</weight>
    <run>
      <colour>#000000</colour>Text Effects</run>
  </heading>
  <paragraph>
    <run>
      <colour>#000000</colour>To add effects to text, surround them with modifiers</run>
  </paragraph>
  <paragraph>
    <run>
      <colour>#000000</colour>*Bold* will make text </run>
    <run>
      <bold />
      <colour>#000000</colour>Bold</run>
  </paragraph>
  <paragraph>
    <run>
      <colour>#000000</colour>_Underlined_ will make text </run>
    <run>
      <underlined />
      <colour>#000000</colour>Underlined</run>
  </paragraph>
  <paragraph>
    <run>
      <colour>#000000</colour>~Italic~ will make the text </run>
    <run>
      <italic />
      <colour>#000000</colour>Italic</run>
  </paragraph>
  <paragraph>
    <run>
      <colour>#000000</colour>%Strikethrough% will apply a strikethrough to the </run>
    <run>
      <strikethrough />
      <colour>#000000</colour>text</run>
  </paragraph>
  <paragraph>
    <run>
      <colour>#000000</colour>*Entire lines can have effets applied to them by not closing the modifiers</run>
  </paragraph>
  <paragraph>
    <run>
      <bold />
      <colour>#000000</colour>This entire line will be bold</run>
  </paragraph>
  <paragraph>
    <run>
      <italic />
      <colour>#000000</colour>And this entire line will be italic</run>
  </paragraph>
  <heading>
    <weight>3</weight>
    <run>
      <colour>#000000</colour>Text Colouring</run>
  </heading>
  <paragraph>
    <run>
      <colour>#000000</colour>You can change the colour of text using colour tags. </run>
  </paragraph>
  <paragraph>
    <run>
      <colour>#000000</colour>/col=#ff00ff/This will make this text bright pink!\col\.  See! </run>
    <run>
      <colour>#ff00ff</colour>This will make this text bright pink!</run>
    <run>
      <colour>#000000</colour>. </run>
  </paragraph>
  <paragraph>
    <run>
      <colour>#000000</colour>The colour tags must start and end properly to be counted though. Colour tags that arent closed will be read as plain text</run>
  </paragraph>
  <heading>
    <weight>2</weight>
    <run>
      <colour>#000000</colour>Using tags</run>
  </heading>
  <paragraph>
    <run>
      <colour>#000000</colour>Tags are opened with forwards slashes, /, and closed with backwards slashes, \!</run>
  </paragraph>
  <paragraph>
    <run>
      <colour>#000000</colour>Other tags include /section/ and /break/</run>
  </paragraph>
  <heading>
    <weight>3</weight>
    <run>
      <colour>#000000</colour>Sections</run>
  </heading>
  <paragraph>
    <run>
      <colour>#000000</colour>/section/ </run>
  </paragraph>
  <paragraph>
    <run>
      <colour>#000000</colour>Use sections to strucutre your document. Section opening and closing tags must be on their own separate line!</run>
  </paragraph>
  <paragraph>
    <run>
      <colour>#000000</colour>\section\</run>
  </paragraph>
  <paragraph>
    <run>
      <colour>#000000</colour>/section align=left/</run>
  </paragraph>
  <paragraph>
    <run>
      <colour>#000000</colour>You can also add align attributes to section tags</run>
  </paragraph>
  <paragraph>
    <run>
      <colour>#000000</colour>\section\</run>
  </paragraph>
  <section>
    <align>right</align>
    <paragraph>
      <align>right</align>
      <run>
        <colour>#000000</colour>You can align sections to the </run>
      <run>
        <bold />
        <colour>#000000</colour>right</run>
      <run>
        <colour>#000000</colour>…</run>
    </paragraph>
  </section>
  <section>
    <align>middle</align>
    <paragraph>
      <align>middle</align>
      <run>
        <colour>#000000</colour>Across the entire page if the lines are long enough. Across the </run>
      <run>
        <bold />
        <colour>#000000</colour>middle</run>
      <run>
        <colour>#000000</colour> of the page. It even works with headings too.</run>
    </paragraph>
  </section>
  <section>
    <align>centre</align>
    <heading>
      <weight>4</weight>
      <align>centre</align>
      <run>
        <colour>#000000</colour>This heading is in the centre of the document! </run>
    </heading>
    <paragraph>
      <align>centre</align>
      <run>
        <colour>#000000</colour>To the </run>
      <run>
        <bold />
        <colour>#000000</colour>centre</run>
      <run>
        <colour>#000000</colour>…</run>
    </paragraph>
  </section>
  <paragraph>
    <run>
      <colour>#000000</colour>
    </run>
  </paragraph>
  <heading>
    <weight>3</weight>
    <run>
      <colour>#000000</colour>Breaks</run>
  </heading>
  <paragraph>
    <run>
      <colour>#000000</colour>/break/ adds a page break to your document. See you on the next page.</run>
  </paragraph>
  <page_break />
  <heading>
    <weight>2</weight>
    <run>
      <colour>#000000</colour>Lists</run>
  </heading>
  <paragraph>
    <run>
      <colour>#000000</colour>There are two types of lists you can use!</run>
  </paragraph>
  <list>
    <list_type>ordered</list_type>
    <o_list_item>
      <list_id>2</list_id>
      <run>
        <colour>#000000</colour>Ordered Lists</run>
    </o_list_item>
    <o_list_item>
      <list_id>2</list_id>
      <run>
        <colour>#000000</colour>Unordered Lists</run>
    </o_list_item>
  </list>
  <paragraph>
    <run>
      <colour>#000000</colour>1.Ordered lists are made by typing a number followed by a full stop at the start of a line.</run>
  </paragraph>
  <paragraph>
    <run>
      <colour>#000000</colour>-Use a dash at the start for a unordered list!</run>
  </paragraph>
  <list>
    <list_type>unordered</list_type>
    <u_list_item>
      <list_id>1</list_id>
      <run>
        <colour>#000000</colour>You don’t need to keep track of the numbers at the start of lines in ordered lists</run>
    </u_list_item>
    <u_list_item>
      <list_id>1</list_id>
      <run>
        <colour>#000000</colour>They count automatically for you!</run>
    </u_list_item>
    <u_list_item>
      <list_id>1</list_id>
      <run>
        <colour>#000000</colour>If you wanted you could always use 1.</run>
    </u_list_item>
  </list>
  <list>
    <list_type>ordered</list_type>
    <o_list_item>
      <list_id>4</list_id>
      <run>
        <colour>#000000</colour>See,</run>
    </o_list_item>
    <o_list_item>
      <list_id>4</list_id>
      <run>
        <colour>#000000</colour>Easy</run>
    </o_list_item>
    <o_list_item>
      <list_id>4</list_id>
      <run>
        <colour>#000000</colour>You’ll have to trust that these all start with 1.!</run>
    </o_list_item>
  </list>
  <paragraph>
    <run>
      <colour>#000000</colour>
    </run>
  </paragraph>
